{"title_page": "Andrianna Campbell", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|American art curator and art historian}}\n'''Andrianna Campbell-LaFleur''' is an American [[art curator|curator]] and [[art historian]] specializing in nineteenth and twentieth-century [[American art]].\n\nCampbell studied at the [[Rhode Island School of Design]] (RISD), where she received her [[Bachelor of Fine Arts|BFA]] in [[printmaking]] with a concentration in art history. While at RISD, the [[Rhode Island School of Design Museum|RISD Museum]] awarded her a [[Carnegie Fellowship]]. She then worked as the associate curator at [[Forbes]], where she managed an international art collection.<ref>{{cite web |title=Spotlight On Andrianna Campbell |url=http://adht.parsons.edu/blog/spotlight-on-andrianna-campbell/ |website=School of Art and Design History and Theory |publisher=[[Parsons School of Design]] |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |date=October 3, 2013}}</ref> She is currently a [[Doctor of Fine Arts|doctorate]] student in the Department of Art History at the [[Graduate Center, CUNY]].<ref name=\"Cohen\">{{cite news |last1=Cohen |first1=Alina |title=The 7 Most Influential Art Critics Today |url=https://observer.com/2018/05/the-7-most-influential-art-critics-today/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=[[The New York Observer]] |date=May 9, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"CUNY\">{{cite web |title=Andrianna Campbell |url=https://www.gc.cuny.edu/Page-Elements/Academics-Research-Centers-Initiatives/Doctoral-Programs/Art-History/Student-Bios/Andrianna-Campbell |website=The [[Graduate Center]] |publisher=[[Graduate Center, CUNY]] |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nCampbell has authored essays on contemporary art for ''[[Artforum]]'', ''[[Art in America]]'', and ''[[Frieze (magazine)|frieze]]''. In 2016, she co-edited an edition of the ''[[International Review of African American Art]]'' dedicated to [[Norman Lewis]]. She is also a founding editor of ''apricota'', a journal focused on art writing and art history, alongside Joanna Fiduccia.<ref name=\"Cohen\" /><ref name=\"CUNY\" />\n\n== Work ==\nPrior to the [[2017 Women's March]], Campbell collaborated with [[MoveOn.org]] to encourage artists to create graphics, signs, and slogans that would, according to Campbell, \"promote positive change, not perpetuate the negative rhetoric coming from the President-elect.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gotthardt |first1=Alexxa |title=Artists Amplify the Power of Protest Signs |url=https://www.artsy.net/article/artsy-editorial-artists-amplify-power-protest-signs |website=[[Artsy]] |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |language=en |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028143416/https://www.artsy.net/article/artsy-editorial-artists-amplify-power-protest-signs |archivedate=October 28, 2017 |date=January 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Campbell opened a [[pop-up shop]] titled Anger Management with visual artist [[Marilyn Minter]] inside of the [[Brooklyn Museum]] to serve as an [[protest art|outlet of protest]] for more than 70 artists, of which Campbell and Minter recruited as vendors for the shop. The proceeds from the shop would be distributed between [[Planned Parenthood]], the [[American Civil Liberties Union]], or a different charity of an artist's choice. Discussing the venture, Campbell commented that \"circulating images, like those created by the Anger Management vendors, contributes to a feeling of solidarity\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moss |first1=Hilary |title=Artists Who Peddle Products \u2014 and Politics |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/02/t-magazine/art/artist-pop-up-marilyn-minter-miranda-july-konig.html |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=[[T (magazine)|T]] |date=October 2, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171006153717/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/02/t-magazine/art/artist-pop-up-marilyn-minter-miranda-july-konig.html |archivedate=October 6, 2017 |url-access=registration}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Eckardt |first1=Stephanie |title=Thongs, Temporary Tattoos, and Other Fun Ways Barbara Kruger, Marilyn Minter, and 70 Other Angry Artists Are Now Resisting Donald Trump |url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/marilyn-minter-brooklyn-museum-protest-art-merch-shop/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=[[W (magazine)|W]] |date=September 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Halperin |first1=Julia |title=Need a Protest Thong? Marilyn Minter Has Opened an Unusual Pop-Up Store to Arm the Resistance |url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/anger-management-brooklyn-museum-1097642 |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=[[Artnet]] News |date=September 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://andriannacampbell.com/}}\n* [http://gc-cuny.academia.edu/ACampbell Andrianna Campbell] on [[Academia.edu]]\n* [https://www.artforum.com/contributor/andrianna-campbell Andrianna Campbell] on [[Artforum]]\n* {{Instagram|id=andriannacampbelllafleur|name=Andrianna Campbell}}\n* [https://frieze.com/article/women-arts-andrianna-campbell Women in the Arts: Andrianna Campbell] (article in ''[[Frieze (magazine)|frieze]]'')\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Campbell, Andrianna}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century African-American women]]\n[[Category:American curators]]\n[[Category:American art curators]]\n[[Category:American art critics]]\n[[Category:American art historians]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island School of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|American art curator and art historian}}\n'''Andrianna Campbell-LaFleur''' is an American [[art curator|curator]] and [[art historian]] specializing in nineteenth and twentieth-century [[American art]].\n\nCampbell studied at the [[Rhode Island School of Design]] (RISD), where she received her [[Bachelor of Fine Arts|BFA]] in [[printmaking]] with a concentration in art history. While at RISD, the [[Rhode Island School of Design Museum|RISD Museum]] awarded her a [[Carnegie Fellowship]]. She then worked as the associate curator at [[Forbes]], where she managed an international art collection.<ref>{{cite web |title=Spotlight On Andrianna Campbell |url=http://adht.parsons.edu/blog/spotlight-on-andrianna-campbell/ |website=School of Art and Design History and Theory |publisher=[[Parsons School of Design]] |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |date=October 3, 2013}}</ref> She is currently a [[Doctor of Fine Arts|doctorate]] student in the Department of Art History at the [[Graduate Center, CUNY]].<ref name=\"Cohen\">{{cite news |last1=Cohen |first1=Alina |title=The 7 Most Influential Art Critics Today |url=https://observer.com/2018/05/the-7-most-influential-art-critics-today/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=[[The New York Observer]] |date=May 9, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"CUNY\">{{cite web |title=Andrianna Campbell |url=https://www.gc.cuny.edu/Page-Elements/Academics-Research-Centers-Initiatives/Doctoral-Programs/Art-History/Student-Bios/Andrianna-Campbell |website=The [[Graduate Center]] |publisher=[[Graduate Center, CUNY]] |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nCampbell has authored essays on contemporary art for ''[[Artforum]]'', ''[[Art in America]]'', and ''[[Frieze (magazine)|frieze]]''. In 2016, she co-edited an edition of the ''[[International Review of African American Art]]'' dedicated to [[Norman Lewis]]. She is also a founding editor of ''apricota'', a journal focused on art writing and art history, alongside Joanna Fiduccia.<ref name=\"Cohen\" /><ref name=\"CUNY\" />\n\n== Work ==\nPrior to the [[2017 Women's March]], Campbell collaborated with [[MoveOn.org]] to encourage artists to create graphics, signs, and slogans that would, according to Campbell, \"promote positive change, not perpetuate the negative rhetoric coming from the President-elect.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gotthardt |first1=Alexxa |title=Artists Amplify the Power of Protest Signs |url=https://www.artsy.net/article/artsy-editorial-artists-amplify-power-protest-signs |website=[[Artsy]] |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |language=en |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028143416/https://www.artsy.net/article/artsy-editorial-artists-amplify-power-protest-signs |archivedate=October 28, 2017 |date=January 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Campbell opened a [[pop-up shop]] titled Anger Management with visual artist [[Marilyn Minter]] inside of the [[Brooklyn Museum]] to serve as an [[protest art|outlet of protest]] for more than 70 artists, of which Campbell and Minter recruited as vendors for the shop. The proceeds from the shop would be distributed between [[Planned Parenthood]], the [[American Civil Liberties Union]], or a different charity of an artist's choice. Discussing the venture, Campbell commented that \"circulating images, like those created by the Anger Management vendors, contributes to a feeling of solidarity\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moss |first1=Hilary |title=Artists Who Peddle Products \u2014 and Politics |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/02/t-magazine/art/artist-pop-up-marilyn-minter-miranda-july-konig.html |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=[[T (magazine)|T]] |date=October 2, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171006153717/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/02/t-magazine/art/artist-pop-up-marilyn-minter-miranda-july-konig.html |archivedate=October 6, 2017 |url-access=registration}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Eckardt |first1=Stephanie |title=Thongs, Temporary Tattoos, and Other Fun Ways Barbara Kruger, Marilyn Minter, and 70 Other Angry Artists Are Now Resisting Donald Trump |url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/marilyn-minter-brooklyn-museum-protest-art-merch-shop/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=[[W (magazine)|W]] |date=September 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Halperin |first1=Julia |title=Need a Protest Thong? Marilyn Minter Has Opened an Unusual Pop-Up Store to Arm the Resistance |url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/anger-management-brooklyn-museum-1097642 |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=[[Artnet]] News |date=September 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://andriannacampbell.com/}}\n* [http://gc-cuny.academia.edu/ACampbell Andrianna Campbell] on [[Academia.edu]]\n* [https://www.artforum.com/contributor/andrianna-campbell Andrianna Campbell] on [[Artforum]]\n* [https://www.instagram.com/andriannacampbelllafleur Andrianna Campbell] on [[Instagram]]\n* [https://frieze.com/article/women-arts-andrianna-campbell Women in the Arts: Andrianna Campbell] (article in ''[[Frieze (magazine)|frieze]]'')\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Campbell, Andrianna}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century African-American women]]\n[[Category:American curators]]\n[[Category:American art curators]]\n[[Category:American art critics]]\n[[Category:American art historians]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island School of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Aranya", "label": "safe", "comment": "ig template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrianna_Campbell"}
